Abstract

The purpose of this project was to create a gaming console with an omnidirectional screen. Traditional multiplayer gaming often suffers from restricted viewing angles when players are clustered around a single two-dimensional screen. To solve this the Omni-Cube uses an “Andotrope” which is a display visible from 360°. An Andotrope has one or two rotating screens in a cylindrical housing with a slit in. For the display two 7” TFT displays were used with RA8875 as drivers. The Andotrope is driven by a high-torque DC motor. The component that runs the main codes is a Raspberry Pi 3 model B and its code is written in CircuitPython. The Raspberry Pi is mounted on the stationary bottom half of the chassis and needs to be connected with SPI pins to the RA8875 drivers located in the dynamic top half that is continuously rotating. A slipring is used for this. The project also has two controllers that communicate wirelessly with the Raspberry Pi using Bluetooth Low Energy. Both controllers use a Seeed Studio XIAO ESP32-S3 coded with C++ to read the states of the buttons and to connect to the Raspberry Pi via BLE. 

The chassis was designed using Fusion 360 and manufactured via 3D printing with PLA filament to ensure structural integrity. Throughout the development process, significant hardware challenges were addressed, specifically regarding the torque requirements which made it necessary to upgrade the motor, and the initial incompatibility of display drivers which led to the adoption of the RA8875 system.

The Omni-Cube only has one playable game implemented, which is a version of Pong. During the planning phase of the project, more games were planned, but had to be cut from the final version due to time constraints. Despite these constraints, the final prototype successfully demonstrates a stable 360° viewing angle and low-latency wireless controllers. While the hardware functions as intended, some graphical flickering appears due to limitations in the used library, but is not very noticeable due to how the graphics are drawn.
